ory, Engine of modernity argues that the omnibus was a metaphor through which writers and artists explored evolving social dynamics of class and gender, meditated on the meaning of progress and change, and reflected on one's own literary and artistic practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCarriages and carts in literature. 0aHorse-drawn omnibuseszFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aClass relations.  aGender and urban space.  aModernity.  aNineteenth century.  aOmnibus.  aParis.  aPopular literature.  aPublic transport.  aSocial relations.  aTransportation in literature.1 aBelenky, Masha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526138606zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526138606zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526138606/original  a978-3-11-128248-0 Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA